	</example>
      </page>
    </worksheet>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-perpendicular">
    <title>Perpendicular Lines</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-perpendicular">
      <title>Perpendicular Lines</title>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Two lines are <term>perpendicular</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Line</h>
	    <h>Perpendicular</h>
	  </idx>
	  if they intersect at a right angle.
	</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <figure xml:id="fig-perpendicular_lines">
      <caption>Perpendicular lines.</caption>
      <image xml:id="img-perpendicular_lines">
	<latex-image xml:id="tikz-perpendicular_lines">
	  <xi:include parse="text" href="tex/perpendicular.tex"/>
	</latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-perpendicular">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Two lines are perpendicular if and only if the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example component="web">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Determine whether the lines
	  <me>3x + 5y = 7
	  \quad\text{and}\quad
	  -5x + 3y = 21
	  </me>
	  are perpendicular.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  First we place the lines in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref> to find the slopes.
	  The first equation becomes
	  <md>
	    <mrow>\amp 3x + 5y = 7 \amp \amp \text{Subtract}\ 3x\ \text{from both sides}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp 5y = -3x + 7 \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 5</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{-3x + 7}{5} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = -\frac{3}{5}x + \frac{7}{5}</mrow>
	  </md>
	  In this form, we can read off the slope of the line as <m>-3/5.</m>
	</p>
	<p>
	  The second equation becomes
	  <md>
	    <mrow>\amp -5x + 3y = 21 \amp\amp \text{Add}\ 5x\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp 3y = 5x + 21 \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 3</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{5x + 21}{3} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{5}{3}x + 7</mrow>
	  </md>
	  In this form, we can read off the slope of the line as <m>5/3</m>.
	</p>
	<p>
	  Finally, to check whether these lines are parallel, we compute the product of these slopes.
	  Since
	  <me>-\frac{3}{5} \times \frac{5}{3} = -\frac{15}{15} = -1</me>
	  we conclude that these lines are perpendicular by <xref ref="thm-perpendicular"/>.
	</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example component="web">
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Find the equation of a line perpendicular to <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> that passes through the point <m>(3,5)</m>.
	  Write your answer in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="custom"> slope-intercept form</xref>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  First, place the line in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>
	  <md>
	    <mrow>\amp 2x + 3y = 5 \amp\amp \text{Subtract}\ 2x\ \text{from both sides}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp 3y = -2x + 5 \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 3</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{-2x + 5}{3} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = -\frac{2}{3}x + \frac{5}{3}.</mrow>
	  </md>
	  We can read off the slope as <m>-2/3</m> from this equation.
	</p>
	<p>
	  To find the slope, <m>m</m>, of a perpendicular line, <xref ref="thm-perpendicular"/> tells us we must solve the equation
	  <me>-\frac{2}{3} m = -1</me>
	  for <m>m</m>:
	  <md>
	    <mrow>\amp -\frac{2}{3} m = -1 \amp\amp \text{Multiply both sides by}\ -\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp -\frac{3}{2}\left(-\frac{2}{3}m\right) = -\frac{3}{2}\left(-1\right) \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp m = \frac{3}{2}.</mrow>
	  </md>
	</p>
	<p>
	  Using <xref ref="thm-point_slope" text="custom">point-slope form</xref>, the equation of the line perpendicular to <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> that passes through the point <m>(3,5)</m> is
	  <me>y - 5 = \frac{3}{2}(x - 3).</me>
	  Finally, we convert to <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>
	  <md>
	    <mrow>\amp y - 5 = \frac{3}{2}(x - 3) \amp \amp \text{Distribute}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y - 5 = \frac{3}{2}x - \frac{9}{2} \amp\amp \text{Add}\ 5\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{3}{2}x - \frac{9}{2} + 5 \amp\amp \text{Find a common denominator}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{3}{2} x - \frac{9}{2} + \frac{10}{2} \amp \amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	    <mrow>\amp y = \frac{3}{2}x + \frac{1}{2}.</mrow>
	  </md>
	</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

